int-org-section.p:
The treaty establishing the European Atomic Energy Community (Euratom) came into force on 1 January 1958. This was designed to encourage the growth of the nuclear energy industry in the Community by conducting research, providing access to information, supplying nuclear fuels, building reactors and establishing common laws and procedures. A common market for nuclear materials was introduced in 1959 and there is a common insurance scheme against nuclear risks. In 1977 the Commission began granting loans on behalf of Euratom to finance investment in nuclear power stations and the enrichment of fissile materials. An agreement with the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) entered into force in the same year, to facilitate co-operation in research on nuclear safeguards and controls. The EU’s Joint Research Centre (JRC, see 

                    Research and Innovation

) conducts research on nuclear safety and the management of radioactive waste.

The EU promoted trans-European networks (TENs, see also 

                    Transport

), with the aim of developing European energy, telecommunications and transport through the interconnection and opening up of national networks. Revised guidelines for the TEN-Energy (TEN-E) programme were adopted by the Council in July 2006, and a revised TEN-E regulation entered into force in June 2022, which established new rules on cross-border energy infrastructure; aimed to further develop the EU offshore strategy and encourage co-operation between member states in the generation of offshore renewable energy; and supported hydrogen transport networks. In November 2013 the European Parliament (EP) approved the EU’s new infrastructure policy, with the introduction of the new Connecting Europe Facility (CEF) for the fields of transport, energy and telecommunications. The CEF was allocated funds for energy of €5,180m. for 2021–27 (in 2018 prices).

In July 2020 the Commission adopted new strategies for the integration of energy systems and for investment in the use of clean hydrogen technologies to help to achieve its objectives. It was envisaged that the contribution of renewable hydrogen to EU energy production would increase from less than 2% in 2018 to 13%–14% by 2050. In July 2021 the Commission adopted proposals on `Delivering the European Green Deal’, confirming a Europe 2030 emissions reduction target of at least 55% by 2030 (`Fit for 55’), in comparison with 1990 levels, and the intention for the EU to be `carbon neutral’ by 2050. Five pieces of `Fit for 55’ legislation were adopted by the Council in April 2023, revising the EU ETS (see above). In its programme for 2023, the Commission stated that it aimed to establish a `hydrogen bank’ that would assist in the scaling up of the EU green hydrogen economy and invest in developing a hydrogen market; a first pilot auction for €800m. in subsidies payable to producers of renewable hydrogen was launched in November. In February 2023 the Commission put forward the Green Deal Industrial Plan, which would aim to increase the production capacity of key green technologies in the EU (see 

                    Internal Market, Industry, Entrepreneurship and Small and Medium-sized Enterprises

).
